[[File:Tsurugi-jinja (Hofu), torii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Torii with {{ill|Mt. Mitake (Yamaguchi)|ja|右田ヶ岳}} in the background}}]]

'''Tsurugi Shrine''' (劔神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Hōfu|ja|防府市}}, {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture|ja|山口県}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社}} and was formerly ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha (shrine)|ja|郷社}} under the old shrine ranking system.

== Enshrined deity ==
* {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素戔嗚尊}}

== History ==
The shrine's origins are unclear. According to legend, it was founded during the reign of Emperor {{ill|Chūai|ja|仲哀天皇}} (14th Emperor of Japan) when he prayed for victory over foreign invaders, enshrining a sacred sword (八握剣) as the {{ill|shintai|ja|神体}}. It was originally located upstream along the Tsurugi River at a site called Katsuzaka and was relocated to its current location around 1595 (Bunroku 4).

In {{ill|867|ja|貞観9th year }}, it is recorded in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}} that the shrine, referred to as "Kenjin" (剣神), was promoted from {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade}} to {{ill|Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正五位下|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade}}.

The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳}} compiled in 927, as "Tsurugi Shrine" located in Saba District of {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国}}.

During the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代}}, the shrine was revered as a god of martial prowess by the {{ill|Ōuchi clan|ja|大内氏}}, and in the {{ill|Azuchi-Momoyama period|ja|安土桃山時代}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi}} prayed here during his Kyushu campaign, offering a drum upon his victorious return.

The shrine sustained damage during the {{ill|July 2009 Chūgoku and Northern Kyushu heavy rain|ja|平成21年7月中国・九州北部豪雨|zh|2009年日本西部暴雨}} due to landslides.

== Annual Festivals ==
* {{ill|Kinensai|ja|祈年祭}} (April 10)
* Prayer Festival for Bountiful Harvest & Family Safety (July 20)
* Main Annual Festival (September 27–28)
* {{ill|Niiname-sai|ja|新嘗祭}} (December 5)

