'''Tsurugi Shrine''' (劔神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Hōfu|ja|防府市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture|ja|山口県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}} and was formerly ranked as a {{ill|Gōsha (shrine)|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}} under the old shrine ranking system.

== Enshrined deity ==
* {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素戔嗚尊|12=draft|12=draft}}

== History ==
The shrine's origins are unclear. According to legend, it was founded during the reign of Emperor {{ill|Chūai|ja|仲哀天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} (14th Emperor of Japan) when he prayed for victory over foreign invaders, enshrining a sacred sword (八握剣) as the {{ill|shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was originally located upstream along the Tsurugi River at a site called Katsuzaka and was relocated to its current location around 1595 (Bunroku 4).

In {{ill|867|ja|貞観9th year|12=draft|12=draft}}, it is recorded in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|12=draft|12=draft}} that the shrine, referred to as "Kenjin" (剣神), was promoted from {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|正五位下|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The shrine is listed in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|12=draft|12=draft}} compiled in 927, as "Tsurugi Shrine" located in Saba District of {{ill|Suō Province|ja|周防国|12=draft|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was revered as a god of martial prowess by the {{ill|Ōuchi clan|ja|大内氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, and in the {{ill|Azuchi-Momoyama period|ja|安土桃山時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}} prayed here during his Kyushu campaign, offering a drum upon his victorious return.

The shrine sustained damage during the {{ill|July 2009 Chūgoku and Northern Kyushu heavy rain|ja|平成21年7月中国・九州北部豪雨|zh|2009年日本西部暴雨|12=draft|12=draft}} due to landslides.

